            <div type="translation" xml:lang="en" resp="#JP">
                <p>The three units of infantry who served at the time of Apollonios son of Apollonios, and the ephebes of his year (honour) Antallos Ornichas, son of Antallos, grandson of Antallos who held the office of gymnasiarch, for the sake of good will.</p>
            </div>
            <div type="commentary">
                <p><!--commented out pending revision-->
                    <!--in honour of Antallos, son of Antallos, g'son of Antallos, Ornichas, the gymnasiarch, erected by three units of foot soldiers, under Apollonios, son of Apollonios and the ephebes. This inscr. well discussed by M-P; Cf. Tusa, Kokalos 9 (1963), 186 for a C3 BC inscr. with the same family of Apollonios, probably; Note IG 14.256 for same names (Antallos Orniches) at Phintias, if genuine, and another gymnasiarch; signif of local troops; poss. relevance of inscr. to status of the town post-Augustus - cf. CIL 10.7336, for classic latin inscr. by the r.p.Soluntinorum decreto decurionum, vs. this, earlier, in Greek; 'la presenza dell'efebia a Solunto... insieme con le documentate testimonianze della hirothytia e della amphipolia (other inscrs'),... ci conferma la grecita di Solnto che, risorta nel IV secolo - con pianta greca - sul monte Catalfano, ha sentito secondo il Tusa, l'influenza di Siracusa...'. I have two slides of this (whole, and detail). On display in courtyard of Palermo Museum (July 2002); cf. also SEG 41.836 for another inscr. with, prob., the grandfather of this individual. Cordiano publishes the text, follows IGLPa and seems unaware of Wilson. IGLPa p.146 offers some thoughts on the military signif of the inscr: record poss. of a military expedition, poss. w/in R army, although 'strateuomai' can simply mean enrolled in 'servizio di leva'; notes the general lack of evidence for recruitment of Sicilians into the legions, after Forni 1953, but also notes Mommsen's point that such lack of evidence is only a weak arg. ex silentio; in this context, cf. Scibona 1971 from Halaesa; long digression on status and Solunto's relatively favourable position. State of stone: minor damage to the sides, loss of corner upper right; 14.5cm high, 67.5cm wide, 7.5cm thick; letters 4-4.5 cm high. Letters incised 'a pennino'. Cordiano really has nothing to add and is based on IGLPa. Wilson 1988: 191 argues for a pre-Augustan date, and in particular for the period of Sextus Pompey (but only b/c it is most unsettled period); on the C1 AD date he comments 'in which case it would document the survival fo such typically hellenistic offices as the gymnasiarch into the Empire, a survival which would not be surprising in Sicily but is not elsewhere documented'; for W., letter-forms are not inconsistent with a C1 BC date.  Wilson 1990 contains the same opinion. Wilson 1990, caption to fig. 33, p.43: ‘The date is uncertain, but the terminology is wholly that of hellenistic practice; both letter forms and the use of marble fo rht inscription (one of the earliest examples in this material in Sicily) rule out a date before the first cetnury B.C. The reference to troops suggests the third quarter fo the first century B.C., probably under Sextus Pompey who perforce rafted many Sicilians into his army, or else under Octoavian immediately afterwards in the years leading up to Actium [NB, Roger prepared to accept an earlier more general C1 BC context, pers.comm.] Taxies in line 1 is the Doric form of taxeis. Gymnasiarchs or gymansia are attested on hellenistic inscritpions at over a dozen Sicilian cities (including Agrigento, Toarmina, Haluntium, Noto, Paternò, and Syracuse), and although it would not be remarkable if this typically Greek hellenistic institution continued to exist during the early Empire, at least in non-chartered communities (in the Greek East it remained common until the fourth century), no securely dated inscription from the island has yet confirmed such a survival’. Masson in CE 1974 rejects IGLPa's view that Ornichan is a gentive plural denoting a family, and at length makes the point that it is a surname, as is common in Sicily; that this was pointed out already in 1866 by Ritschl; that the name finds parallels esp. in Egypt, which sugg. it is of a type linked to a trade / craft - in this case, a 'seller of chickens', a 'poulterer'. Wilson observes, contra IGLPa, that Apollonius should be eponymous, not gymnasiarch.--></p>
            </div>
